{"title_page": "Kalevi Eskelinen", "text_new": "{{short description|Finnish cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Kalevi Eskelinen\n| image          =\n| caption        =\n| fullname       = Kalevi Eskelinen\n| nickname       =\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1945|10|9|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Sonkaj\u00e4rvi]], [[Finland]]\n| death_date     =\n| death_place    =\n| height         =\n| weight         =\n| currentteam    =\n| discipline     =\n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      =\n| amateuryears1  =\n| amateurteam1   =\n| proyears1      =\n| proteam1       =\n| majorwins      =\n| medaltemplates =\n| show-medals    =\n| updated        =\n}}\n\n'''Kalevi Eskelinen''' (born 9 October 1945) is a Finnish former [[bicycle racing|racing cyclist]]. He won the [[Finnish National Road Race Championships|Finnish national road race title]] in 1969.<ref name=\"CyclingArchives\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cyclingarchives.com/coureurfiche.php?coureurid=53666 |title=Kalevi Eskelinen |accessdate=5 May 2014 |work=Cycling Archives}}</ref> Additionally, he competed at the [[1972 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/es/kalevi-eskelinen-1.html |title=Kalevi Eskelinen |accessdate=5 May 2014 |work=Sports Reference}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cycling archives|53666}}\n\n{{Finnish National Road Race Championships (men) |state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eskelinen, Kalevi}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Finnish male cyclists]]\n[[Category:People from Sonkaj\u00e4rvi]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of Finland]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1972 Summer Olympics]]\n{{Finland-cycling-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Finnish cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Kalevi Eskelinen\n| image          =\n| caption        =\n| fullname       = Kalevi Eskelinen\n| nickname       =\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1945|10|9|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Sonkaj\u00e4rvi]], [[Finland]]\n| death_date     =\n| death_place    =\n| height         =\n| weight         =\n| currentteam    =\n| discipline     =\n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      =\n| amateuryears1  =\n| amateurteam1   =\n| proyears1      =\n| proteam1       =\n| majorwins      =\n| medaltemplates =\n| show-medals    =\n| updated        =\n}}\n\n'''Kalevi Eskelinen''' (born 9 October 1945) is a Finnish former [[bicycle racing|racing cyclist]]. He won the [[Finnish National Road Race Championships|Finnish national road race title]] in 1969.<ref name=\"CyclingArchives\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cyclingarchives.com/coureurfiche.php?coureurid=53666 |title=Kalevi Eskelinen |accessdate=5 May 2014 |work=Cycling Archives}}</ref> Additionally, he competed at the [[1972 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/es/kalevi-eskelinen-1.html |title=Kalevi Eskelinen |accessdate=5 May 2014 |work=Sports Reference}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cycling archives|53666}}\n\n{{Finnish National Road Race Championships (men) |state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eskelinen, Kalevi}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Finnish male cyclists]]\n[[Category:People from Sonkaj\u00e4rvi]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of Finland]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1972 Summer Olympics]]\n{{Finland-cycling-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kalevi_Eskelinen"}
{"title_page": "St John The Baptist Church, Buxton", "text_new": "{{Infobox church\n| name = St John The Baptist Church, Buxton\n| pushpin label position = \n| image = Church of St. John the Baptist.JPG\n| imagesize = \n| imagelink = \n| imagealt = \n| landscape = \n| caption = St John The Baptist Church, Buxton\n| latNS = \n| founder = \n| pushpin map alt = \n| pushpin mapsize = \n| map caption = \n| latd = \n| latm = \n| lats = \n| pushpin map = \n| longd = \n| dedication = [[John The Baptist|St John The Baptist]]\n| previous denomination = \n| longEW = \n| coordinates = {{coord|53|15|32.13|N|1|55|2.21|W|display=inline,title|region:GB_scale:2000}}\n| osgraw = <!--  TEXT -->\n| osgridref = <!-- {{gbmappingsmall|TEXT}} -->\n| location = [[Buxton, Derbyshire]]\n| country = [[England]]\n| longm = \n| longs = \n| churchmanship = \n| membership = \n| attendance = \n| website = \n| former name = \n| bull date = \n| founded date = \n| spire height = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n| fullname = \n| construction cost = \n| cult = \n| relics = \n| events = \n| past bishop = \n| people = \n| functional status = \n| heritage designation = [[Grade II* listed]]<ref name=\"Listing\">{{NHLE |num=1258025|desc=Church of St John The Baptist|access-date=19 March 2020 |mode=cs2 |fewer-links=yes}}</ref>\n| status = \n| designated date = \n| architect = \n| architectural type = \n| style = \n| groundbreaking = \n| completed date = \n| consecrated date = \n| dedicated date = \n| floor count = \n| floor area = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n| length = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n| width = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n| width nave = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n| height = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n| diameter = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n| other dimensions = \n| demolished date = \n| closed date = \n| dome quantity = \n| dome height outer = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n| dome height inner = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n| dome dia outer = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n| dome dia inner = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n| spire quantity = \n| capacity = \n| denomination = [[Church of England]]\n| materials = \n| canonchancellor = \n| diocese = [[Diocese of Derby|Derby]]\n| bell weight = \n| parish = Buxton\n| deanery = Peak Deanery\n| archdeaconry = Chesterfield\n| episcopalarea = \n| archdiocese = \n| subdivision = \n| vicar = \n| province = [[Province of Canterbury|Canterbury]]\n| presbytery = \n| synod = \n| circuit = \n| district = \n| division = \n| metropolis = \n| archbishop = \n| curate = \n| canon = \n| provost = \n| provost-rector = \n| viceprovost = \n| subdean = \n| precentor = \n| chancellor = \n| bishop = \n| dean = \n| canonmissioner = \n| canonpastor = \n| canontreasurer = \n| succentor = \n| archdeacon = \n| prebendary = \n| rector = \n| bells = \n| bells hung = \n| organist = \n| asstpriest = \n| minister = \n| assistant = \n| honpriest = \n| deacon = \n| seniorpastor = \n| pastor = \n| deaconness = \n| abbot = \n| chaplain = \n| reader = \n| student intern = \n| organistdom = \n| director = \n| priest = \n| priestincharge = \n| youthmin = \n| flowerguild = \n| warden = \n| verger = \n| businessmgr = \n| liturgycoord = \n| reledu = \n| rcia = \n| chapterclerk = \n| organscholar = \n| musicgroup = \n| parishadmin = \n| serversguild = \n| logo = \n| logosize = \n| logolink = \n| laychapter = \n| logoalt = \n}}{{Use dmy dates|date = March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n\n'''St John The Baptist Church''' is a [[Grade II* listed]] parish church in the [[Church of England]] in [[Buxton|Buxton, Derbyshire]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1258025|title=CHURCH OF ST JOHN THE BAPTIST, High Peak - 1258025 {{!}} Historic England|website=historicengland.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe church on St John's Road was designed in the Neo-Classical [[Regency era|Regency]] style by John White. It was built between 1802 and 1811 through the patronage of [[William Cavendish, 5th Duke of Devonshire]]. It is constructed from [[Ashlar]] gritstone with a slate roof. In 1896 the architect Sir [[Arthur Blomfield|Authur Blomfield]] redesigned the nave and the original east portico was enclosed to form the chancel. The large pediment on the facade is supported by undecorated Tuscan-style columns and is inscribed prominently with MDCCCXI. The stained glass windows include several by the Victorian designer [[Charles Eamer Kempe]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://buxtonparish.org.uk/our-churches/st-johns-church/|title=THE CHURCH OF ENGLAND Buxton Team Parish {{!}} St. John the Baptist Church|website=buxtonparish.org.uk|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Morten|first=David|title=Buxton in 50 Buildings|publisher=Amberley Publishing Limited|year=2018|isbn=9781445678948|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nSt John's Church became the town's new [[Anglicanism|Anglican]] church (for the growing numbers of residents and visitors, close to the popular spa baths), succeeding [[St Anne's Church, Buxton|St Anne's Church]] in Higher Buxton, which was later converted into a school. St John's initially served the parish of Fairfield until the parish of Buxton was created in 1898.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Langham|first=Mike|title=Buxton: A People's History|publisher=Carnegie Publishing|year=2001|isbn=1-85936-086-6|location=|pages=151}}</ref>\n\nThe church is used as an arts venue during the annual Buxton International Festival.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Parish status ==\nThe church is in a joint parish with\n\n* Christ Church, Burbage\n* Christ Church, King Sterndale\n* [[St Anne's Church, Buxton]]\n* St James' Church, Buxton\n* St Mary's Church, Buxton\n\n== Organ ==\nThe organ was installed by William Hill & Son of London in 1897. A specification of the organ can be found on the [[National Pipe Organ Register]].<ref>{{National Pipe Organ Register|id=N00340|access-date=22 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n<references group=\"\" responsive=\"1\"></references>\n\n[[Category:Grade II* listed buildings in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Grade II* listed churches in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Buxton]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox church\n| name = St John The Baptist Church, Buxton\n| pushpin label position = \n| image = Church of St. John the Baptist.JPG\n| imagesize = \n| imagelink = \n| imagealt = \n| landscape = \n| caption = St John The Baptist Church, Buxton\n| latNS = \n| founder = \n| pushpin map alt = \n| pushpin mapsize = \n| map caption = \n| latd = \n| latm = \n| lats = \n| pushpin map = \n| longd = \n| dedication = [[John The Baptist|St John The Baptist]]\n| previous denomination = \n| longEW = \n| coordinates = {{coord|53|15|32.13|N|1|55|2.21|W|display=inline,title|region:GB_scale:2000}}\n| osgraw = <!--  TEXT -->\n| osgridref = <!-- {{gbmappingsmall|TEXT}} -->\n| location = [[Buxton, Derbyshire]]\n| country = [[England]]\n| longm = \n| longs = \n| churchmanship = \n| membership = \n| attendance = \n| website = \n| former name = \n| bull date = \n| founded date = \n| spire height = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n| fullname = \n| construction cost = \n| cult = \n| relics = \n| events = \n| past bishop = \n| people = \n| functional status = \n| heritage designation = [[Grade II* listed]]<ref name=\"Listing\">{{NHLE |num=1258025|desc=Church of St John The Baptist|access-date=19 March 2020 |mode=cs2 |fewer-links=yes}}</ref>\n| status = \n| designated date = \n| architect = \n| architectural type = \n| style = \n| groundbreaking = \n| completed date = \n| consecrated date = \n| dedicated date = \n| floor count = \n| floor area = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n| length = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n| width = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n| width nave = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n| height = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n| diameter = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n| other dimensions = \n| demolished date = \n| closed date = \n| dome quantity = \n| dome height outer = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n| dome height inner = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n| dome dia outer = <